July 28, 2017 /
Investors, Master Limited Partnerships, oil and gas

Oil and Gas Investment Recommendations From Ronald Clark and Summit Brokerage Services?

Andrew Stoltmann /
fraud, investment fraud, lawsuit, Ronald Clark, Summit Brokerage Services / 

Were you a customer of Ronald Clark of Summit Brokerage Services in Tampa, Florida? If so, the attorneys at Stoltmann Law Offices would like to speak with you about the losses you may have suffered because of his recommendations. Allegedly, Ronald Clark, while employed at Summit Brokerage Services, “did not use mutual fund breakpoints from July 2014 until August 2016,” and recommended an oil and gas investment that suffered losses. That complaint is currently pending. On another occasion, a customer alleged that Clark recommended unsuitable investments that resulted in “great loss” while he was registered with ProEquities. These are against securities rules. A broker has a duty to only recommend those securities that are suitable for his client. If he does not, his brokerage firm may be held liable for investment losses. Please call us today for a no-cost, no-obligation consultation with one of our attorneys. We may be able to help you recover your investment losses on a contingency fee basis. We sue firms in the Financial Industry Regulatory Authority (FINRA) arbitration forum.
Clark was previously registered with John Hancock Distributors, Protective Equity Services, and ProEquities in Tampa, Florida from March 1992 until April 2009. He is currently registered at Summit Brokerage Services in Tampa, Florida and has been since March 2009. He has 10 customer disputes against him, one of which is currently pending.











July 13, 2017 /
Investors, oil and gas, Uncategorized

Please Call 312-332-4200 Today If You Suffered ForceField Energy (FNRG) Losses and Were Recommended the Investment By Gerald Cocuzzo and Newbridge Securities

Andrew Stoltmann /
forcefield energy, fraud, gerald cocuzzo, investment fraud, lawsuit, newbridge securities, oil and gas, oil and gas scams / 

Stoltmann Law Offices continues to investigate Gerald Cocuzzo, a former broker with Newbridge Securities, who allegedly convinced customers to buy investments in ForceField Energy. Cocuzzo is currently serving 18 months in prison after pleading guilty to securities fraud for his role in the fraudulent market manipulation of ForceField Energy (FNRG) on July 7th. FNRG was a distributor of LED lighting products and Cucuzzo allegedly used nominees to purchase and sell FNRG stock without disclosing this information to investors, orchestrating the trading of FNRG to create the misleading appearance of genuine trading volume and interest in the stock and concealing secret payments to stock promoters and broker/dealers who promoted and sold FNRG to investors while falsely claiming to be independent of the company. This scheme cost $131 million in total. Cocuzzo allegedly received cash kickbacks from an FNRG executive in exchange for him purchasing stock in client accounts. If you would like to sue Newbridge Securities for not properly supervising Mr. Cocuzzo, please call our Chicago-based law offices today in order to speak to an attorney for free. There is no obligation. Please call today, as there is a statute of limitations on most cases.











May 31, 2017 /
Master Limited Partnerships, oil and gas, Uncategorized

Oil and Gas Recommendations With Stephen Swarbrick? How To Sue Questar Capital Corp

Andrew Stoltmann /
fraud, investment fraud, lawsuit, oil and gas scams, Questar Capital Corp / 

Recently, a complaint was filed against Stephen Swarbrick with the California Department of Business Oversight alleging unsuitable sales for $400,000 in equipment leasing and oil and gas partnerships for December 2009 through June 2014. Other complaints involve Swarbrick’s sales of alternative investment products such as equipment leasing and oil and as private placements. These can be extremely risky and illiquid investments that are not suitable for all investors. Many investments in oil and gas are risky and illiquid, and a broker must take into account a client’s age, net worth, and investment objectives before recommending an investment. Please call our securities law firm today at 312-332-4200 to find out how you may be able to sue Swarbrick’s firm, Questar Capital Corp if you suffered losses with him. The firm may be liable for those losses because it failed to properly supervise him. The call is free with no obligation. We take cases on a contingency fee basis only. According to his online, FINRA BrokerCheck report, Mr. Swarbrick was registered with Great Western Financial Securities in Northridge, Georgia from June 1994 until May 1998, WM Financial Services in Irvine, California from February 1998 until September 2003 and Woodbury Financial Services in Roseville, California from September 2003 until October 2012. He is currently registered with Questar Capital Corp in Roseville and Cameron Park, California and has been since October 2012. He has two customer disputes against him, one of which is currently pending.











